First Avenue, north from East 36th Street, showing mainly the west side of this thoroughfare. In the foreground is the cleared area for the plaza approach to the Midtown-Queens tunnel.

This property is the fenced zone extending from 36th to 37th Streets. The 37th -38th Street frontage is also being utilized. Beyond, appear the Eletto Warehouse and Tudor City Buildings. To the left is the utilitarian News Building.

Buildings appearing across same are on the south side of E. 35th Street, west of the Avenue. To the right is the rear of the 12 story Harriet Hubbard Ayer Building, No 317-23 E. 34th Street (q.v.). See same for general views of this area.

Somach photo Service
New York City Tunnel Authority

First Avenue, west side, from E. 36th (left) to 37th (right) Streets. The four tenements at the left will be razed in June, joining those that surrounded same. At the right margin appears a portion of the Eletco Co. warehouse which occupies the entire lower end of the 38th -39th Street block.

First Avenue, west side, from E. 36th (left) to 37th Streets, showing the Midtown Queens Tunnel clearance extending to Second Avenue ("El" thereupon). In solitary dignity stands the St. Gabriel's branch of the New York Public Library. This is shortly to come down. Note St. Gabriel's Park at the left and the Empire State Building in the background.

Sept 20, 1939

Nathan Schwartz
New York Public Library

East 36th Street, west of First Avenue, as photographed across the avenue and St. Gabriel's Park. This entire block is to be cleared for the Midtown-Queens Tunnel approach. Note on the right a part of this activity already under way. St. Gabriel's Church and Parochial School were included. Forming a backdrop are the skyscrapers oonstituting the Grand Central-42nd Street outline. From left to right respectively, these are, the Chanin, R. C. A., Chrysler, News, Waldorf-Astoria and General Electric Buildings. The Tudor City Hotel Woodstock is on the right.
1939
Alexander Alland
This photo is one of a series that appeared in the published volume "Portrait of N.Y." by Felix Reisenberg and Alex. Alland, IRGV.

E. 36th Street, west from First Avenue, showing prominently the northeasterly corner of St. Gabriel's Park, viewed southwestward.

Bounding this open area are buildings on 35th Street (left), Second Avenue (center, "El" thereupon) and 36th Street (right(. In the background, at Fifth Avenue and 34th Street, is the huge Empire State Building.

January 8, 1939

Somach Photo Service
New York City Tunnel Authority

East 36th Street, west from First avenue, showing the cleared area extending 1 block square and which will provide an entrance to the new Midtown - Queens Tunnel. Standing alone is the New York Public Library Branch. This will come down in early 1940. The tenements at the right line the north side of East 37th Street. Forming a backdrop are skyscrapers, which from left to right (collective views) are, the Empire State, the 10 East 40th Street, the New York Trust, the Lefcourt Colonial, the 500( Fifth Avenue, the Lincoln, the Chanin and the Chrysler Buildings.
View 1: June 28, 1939
Views 2-3:  July 23, 1939

E. 36th Street, north side, west from (No. 325, right) a point midway between First and Second Avenue and to the latter (left). Shown are St. Gabriel's Parochial School, its Hall and the New York Public Library branch building. To the right are two tenements bearing No's 323 and 325. All of these face the upper end of St. Gabriel's Park and will be found missing in June 1939, having been demolished (exclusive of the Library building) for the approach to the 38th Street tunnel.

January 12, 1939

Somach Photo Service
New York City Tunnel Authority

East 36th Street, north side, west from a point midway between First and Second Avenues, and across the latter, to show St, Gabriels Parochial School under demolition.

The Church of this name is to the rear, facing on the south side of East 37th Street, and is in the same condition.

The three story Hall adjoins the School and will shortly follow. To the west is the New York Public Library branch building identified with this Church. This will remain standing until early 1940 when this will be razed also.

View No. 3 is photographed from St. Gabriels Park and shows the shadowy outlines of the Chrysler and Lincoln Buildings across the School and Library respectively.

No. 1 May 25, 1939
2 May 26, 1939
3 May 27, 1939

East 36th Street, north side, between First and Second Avenues, showing the cleared former site of St. Gabriel's Church and Parochial School. To the left and not shown is the still standing New York Public Library branch.

The "El" line in the midground is on Second Avenue. To the right are tenements on the north side of 37th Street, slightly east of the Avenue. The N.E. corner there is cleared also, the same has no connection with the tunnel project.

Centered in the distance is the spired Chrysler Building, flanked by the Chanin and News structures.

East 36th Street, north side, between First and Second Avenues, showing the Midtown Queens tunnel plaza being cleared.

Workmen are occupied on the former site of St. Gabriel's Church and School.

Across same appear buildings at 37th Street (left of center) and First Avenue (right of center).

The smoke stacks above the former, are atop the Consolidated Edison Co. plant on First Avenue.

Note at the left margin the New York Public Library branch library remaining at this date. Early 1940 will see this razed.

First Avenue is to the right and the photographer is viewing northeastward towards same.
